Thesis 1: Theological Strand
Title:
The Resurrection as Boundary-Encoding Event: A Theological Reading of Phase Transition and Coherence Restoration in the Quantum Logos Framework
Core Question:
How can the Christian doctrines of the Incarnation, the Cross (including the Harrowing of Hell), and the Resurrection be understood as a sequence of phase transitions and boundary-encoding events that move disordered, fallen reality toward incorruptible coherence?
Key Objectives:

Interpret the tearing of the veil and the Resurrection through the lens of holographic boundary encoding and discrete corrective operations (“flicks”).
Explore the Shroud of Turin as a historical and theological witness to information being transfigured and preserved on a 2D boundary.
Examine Forgiveness as the final orientation (Ψ_Final = 1) in which nothing true is lost and all things are brought into coherent, glorified form.
Maintain the integrity of Christian theology while engaging seriously with the physics and information-theoretic language of the model.

Methodology:
Systematic theology combined with careful analogical reasoning. Primary sources: Scripture, patristic writings on the Resurrection and Harrowing of Hell, and the theological layer of the QuantumLogosEngine itself.
Contribution:
Offers a contemporary mystical-theological interpretation of the Resurrection that takes seriously both the historical claims of Christianity and the conceptual tools of modern physics and information theory, without reducing one to the other.
